      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks that works for the basic case. but i'm worried about tests that might return something that isn't easily comparable with `!=`, like if they return complex objects or if they crash sometimes. \n\nactually, i just realized a problem. what if the test is flaky because it occasionally throws an exception instead of returning a different value? like, if it returns `True` sometimes and `Exception` other times? your current code would probably just crash the whole detector.\n\ncan you update it so it handles exceptions? i want it to still return `True` if the function fails in a way that's inconsistent (e.g., it succeeds sometimes and fails others). \n\nhere is an updated test suite i'm thinking of using to verify:\n\n```python\ndef flaky_exception_test():\n    if random.random() < 0.5:\n        return \"success\"\n    else:\n        raise ValueError(\"random failure\")\n\ndef stable_exception_test():\n    # always fails\n    raise ValueError(\"constant failure\")\n\n# flaky_exception_test should be True\nassert detect_flakiness(flaky_exception_test, n_runs=20) == True\n# stable_exception_test should be False (it's consistent, even if it fails)\nassert detect_flakiness(stable_exception_test, n_runs=20) == False\n```\n\ncan you fix the function so it passes these?",
